dataIdInfo.idPurp: This Voting Precinct (polygon) dataset created to represented and validate representative jurisdictions within Harris County Texas. The Voting Precincts comprise of 1,012 individual Voting Precincts (VPCTs) which were reduced from 1,069 VPCTs (2014 dataset) and approved by the Harris County Commissioner Court. The boundaries were digitized through the use of the original 2014 Voting Precincts and by utilizing the following: 2014 Aerial Imagery, US House of Representatives, US Census blocks/Tracts, the Texas Legislative Council's Voter Tabulation Districts (VTD), Texas Senate, Texas House of Representatives, Texas State Board of Education (SBOE), City Limits by Harris County Appraisal District (HCAD), Harris County ISD, HCAD Parcels, and Harris County Municipalities Utility Districts (MUDs).
dataIdInfo.idAbs:
This is vector (polygon) dataset represents 1,012 Voting Precincts in Harris County, Texas - effective January 1st, 2016 changes made complying with the Texas Legislative Council and directed by Harris County Commissioner Court.

Political Jurisdiction boundaries included as part of the attribute table with reference to Plan number of Political Jurisdiction: US House of Representative Plan C235, Texas State Senate Plan S172, Texas House of Representative Plan H358, Texas State Board of Education (SBOE) Plan S120, Harris County Justice of the Peace and Constable, Harris County Commissioner revA1, and Harris County Department of Education (HCDoE).
dataIdInfo.idCredit: Harris County Commissioners Court and Harris County Tax Office

srcCitatn.otherCitDet:
The Texas Legislative Council is a nonpartisan legislative agency that provides bill drafting, computing, research, publishing, and document distribution services to the Texas Legislature and the other legislative agencies. The council also serves as an information resource for state agencies, the citizens of Texas, and others as time and resources allow.
Under the guidance of a 14-member governing body and the general direction of the executive director, the council staff is organized into administrative functions and four divisions: document production, information systems, legal, and research

prcStep.stepDesc: Manual review of the 1,069 2014 Voting Precincts by Registered Voter Population with goal of reducing any Voting Precinct Registered Voters where population exceed 5,000 individuals. 1.1st Review conducted by Voters Mapping Department, through used of geocoding registered voters addresses to 2014 Road data. 2. Maps produced based upon Step 1 of voter population by individual Harris County Commissioner. 3. 2nd Review conducted with Harris County Commissioners and Voters Mapping department. Included Texas Legislative Council Voter Tabulated Districts (VTD) displaying various Federal, State, and County Political Jurisdictions. 4. Results of 2nd Review incorporated into a series of individual Voting Precinct that were identified in about Steps 1 thru 3. 5. Individual Voting Precinct maps were outlined in "green" indicating where those Voting Precincts that were identified as being require to be redrawn or Re-Precincting (term used) as defined by Step 2. 6. Re-Precincting effort was conducted using 2014 Aerial Imagery 6 inch and the various Political Jurisdictions as previous stated in earlier in the metadata. 7. Topology ArcGIS 10.3 was performed to valid if there were overlaps and gaps requiring editing of individual Voting Precinct polygons. Topology has not been validated for these polygons. 8. Quality review undertaken the Voters Manager and Mapping Department to ensure that individual Voting Precinct boundaries were align to the adjacent Voting Precinct boundaries
